subSections.text:
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s-miːt||to extinguish; to shut abruptly; to wink; to blink; to die}}. {{zh-ref|Matisoff}} compares {{cog|my|မှိတ်||(''of eyes'') to close; (''of light'') to put out, to switch off}} and possibly {{cog|bo|མེད||to not exist}}. Cognate Chinese characters include:

* {{och-l|烕|to destroy; to cause destruction}}
* {{och-l|蔑|to destroy}}

The Old Chinese *''e'' ~ Proto-Tibeto-Burman *''i'' vowel discrepancy may be explained by a reanalysis of the proto-etymon in Chinese, as derived from {{och-l|隳|tr=*hmai|to destroy}} + suffix *''-t'' ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2009}}), although {{zh-l|*隳}} is reconstructed in the Baxter-Sagart and Zhengzhang systems as having an *''l''-like initial. The direct Chinese comparandum of Proto-Tibeto-Burman *''mit'' may be {{och-l|沒|to disappear; to die; to perish in water}} ([[ibid.]]).

